<br>
The number one economy -- the whole big picture -- is the U.S. economy. At times other economies grow faster, but they have a lot of catching up to do. <br>
<br>
BTW, how many countries does it take the EU? Does the EU make military and political decisions together? Are they an acting power? <br>
<br>
No, they arent.  So even if all your statements were true, it would not matter because they dont have a government to act as the U.S. acts.  It is a ton of smaller economies combined.  <br>
<br>
And all those members are in massive disagreement about Iraq. So, they arent unified even in decision. <br>
<br>
You are right though. The russians sell more weapons to prop a country stumbling through the harsh and barren economic landscape they received from being an agricultural economy trying to take on the U.S. in a weapons race. <br>
<br>
So, I should have phrased it better.  Who sells more high technology weapons, the weapons that really matter in the broad scheme of things? Ak-47 and 30 year old tanks dont do much. 30-40 year old submarines dont do so much today.  <br>
