<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The combined economies of the EU are slightly smaller than the U.S. economy ($9.2 trillion purchasing power parity gross domestic product for the EU in 2001 versus $9.9 trillion for the United States), while the EU population of 376.8 million significantly exceeds the U.S. population of 278 million. The United States has extensive trade relations with the EU. In 2001, 22% of U.S. exports ($159 billion) went to EU members, and 19% of U.S. imports ($220 billion) originated in EU countries.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--> <br>
<br>
100 million more people in the EU and less purchasing power parity in GDP (thats gross not per cap) so you want to move to per cap numbers and it would look even worse. <br>
<br>
As for the EU being a political unit, it is but it is not the same as a soverign nation.  It does not speak for members military matters, welfare matters, local social and policy matters, or regulatory matters (other than those related to the economy). It does:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>The budget, $99 billion in 2002, finances the common policies like agriculture, research and development, programs linked to the single market<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
So, it functions for the economy that it represents basically and not in forms of foreign policy, self-defense, and police powers.  Three big parts of sovereign nations. <br>
<br>
