<br>
You obviously do not understand Constitutional politics. <br>
Our states do not hold the powers of sovereign nations: Trade, making and controlling the money, military, foreign policy, and broad regulatory powers (inlcuding economic).  <br>
<br>
But thats ok, I understand its hard for you to comprehend these finer points.  Additionally the Constitution gives the federal government the main source of power and only goes to mention that other powers go to the states that is not outlined.  However, the states rights clause as some refer to it is not all inclusive.  The Supreme Court over the years has rewarded more power to the national level that serves in its interests as interpreted by the Constitution.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>local matters are decided by state governments<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
BTW, local means at the municipal level in government terminology.  You meant states decide matters in their state? Only some, things that the federal government does not need to spend their time doing.  However, &quot;local&quot; matters in that regard are different in the &quot;local&quot; matters of the EU nations since they ARE soveriegn nations, not drawing their power from the national government. <br>
<br>
Interstate trade goes to the federal level (most trade in our nation is interstate or international placing it under federal view), actions of the treasury control banking in all states, foreign policy effects the way states must deal with other countries (the president is the soul representative of the U.S. to foreign countries according to the U.S. Constitution), national security and military effects state economies and controls the way they handle their borders, airports, etc... <br>
<br>
These things dont happen all in the EU. A soverign nation does all the above. The EU doesnt even come close to having that kind of interaction.  And BTW, its called federalism, the interaction and sharing of powers between state and federal.  <br>
<br>
On the economic forefront again you lack.  You pick one number to focus on while neglecting the broad picture and simply admitting that its true.  Thats why you want to pick one number.  You want one so you can nitpick without looking at the broad picture.  BTW, you were wrong on purchasing power parity with GDP.  Because my purchasing power number was NOT PER CAP.  You went to per cap because that an easy battle to win when compared to tiny countries with small populations that are industrialized.  You fail to deal with the big picture. <br>
