Yes Drack. All economies depend on each other. However, the main thrust is still true. Until they can find a way to check the U.S. power without harming themselves dramatically, there is nothing they can do about it.  Whether we are right or wrong is moot if you have no way to change it.  You must act to change things which we know is impossible for those UN members against because they like to debate, but not to act in concert.  Which leaves it at the feet of an individual country to make a difference.  When one gets the military and economic ability to handle the worlds humanitarian aid, policing, and other issues, they are welcome to try. <br>
<br>
<br>
In Addition, only 8% of our GDP depends on exports while a far cry greater of those anti-america countries depend on exports (of which a majority go to the U.S.).  We would hurt, sure, by cutting off our borders; however, those who are whining about checking our power are the ones who need to cut us off, not vice versa. We are happy to sell to those who dislike us.  They dislike us so much but they cant vote with their dollars. In the end, they come crawling back needing our aid, our military, and our companies. <br>
<br>
We have nothing to prove by stopping the purchase of their goods either.  We are not closed to products we enjoy because quite simply, our purchase does not give them any true power. <br>
<br>
